            <otmi:snippets>
              <otmi:splitregex>(?-mix:\.\s+(?=[A-Z]))</otmi:splitregex>
              <otmi:snippet>As the microtubules depolymerized, the Dam1 complex slid along the spindle away from the shrinking ends, bearing its cargo of beads</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>As the microtubules shortened during depolymerization, the Dam1 complex could clearly be seen progressing along the microtubules</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Barnes et al . used real-time imaging to watch the Dam1 complex on dynamic microtubules in vitro </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But if these ends are continually dissolving as the microtubules pull back, how do the chromosomes stay attached? The answer lies with a subcomplex in the kinetochore, called the Dam1 complex, which assembles into rings and paired helices that encircle the ends of depolymerizing microtubules (pictured)</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>During cell division, an array of tiny filaments called microtubules spreads from the poles of the cell to the central plane, where the duplicated chromosomes congregate</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>During chromosome segregation, the microtubules depolymerize, and thus shorten, from the end nearest the central plane of the cell</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Finally, Barnes and colleagues showed that the Dam1 complex can function as a coupling device to move objects along the microtubules</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It will be interesting to find out whether chromosomes are transported in the same way.</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Microtubules are linear polymers of the protein tubulin of diameter 24 nm that grow or shrink as tubulin monomers are added to or lost from their ends</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>So, as the spindle shrinks, the attached chromosomes are carried towards the pole</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Streptavidin-coated microbeads were recruited to the microtubules using a biotin-labelled Dam1 complex</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The authors demonstrated that turnover of Dam1-complex subunits was not taking place and that the ring structure is sliding intact along the depolymerizing microtubule</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The chromosomes stick to the depolymerizing ends of the spindle microtubules through specialized protein complexes known as kinetochores</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The details of how these duplicated chromosomes are separated are still being puzzled out, but elsewhere in this issue, Georjana Barnes and colleagues ( Nature 440 , 565 – 569 ; 2006 ) add a large piece to the jigsaw</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>These experiments relied on the strong bonds formed between streptavidin and biotin molecules</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>They labelled the Dam1 complex and the microtubules with different coloured fluorophores</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This microtubule structure — the &quot;mitotic spindle&quot; — is responsible for dragging the two copies of the chromosome apart into the two regions that will form the daughter cells</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This movement could be explained either by a &quot;sliding&quot; mechanism, in which the Dam1 complex is continually associated with the microtubule lattice, or by a &quot;turnover&quot; mechanism, with new subunits of the Dam1 complex rapidly incorporating into existing rings as old subunits leave, thus propelling the ring along the microtubule</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>When cells divide, each chromosome is duplicated and one copy is passed to each daughter cell</otmi:snippet>
